                  <persName id="t18310407-242-person1687">
                  THOMAS 
                  JOSEPH WEST
               <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1687" type="surname" value="JOSEPH WEST"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1687" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1687" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-constable. On the Tuesday before the 5th of March, I was in Hopkin-street, St. James; I saw the prisoner carry something under his arm, into an old iron-shop - I followed him, and saw he had this pair of boots and this chaise rug; he asked if they bought such things - the girl saw me behind him, and said they did not; I asked what he had got - he said an old rug which his master had given him to cut for horse-cloths - I went to inquire at a place he sent me to, and it was denied - I said to him the next morning, "It was useless for you to give me so much trouble last night;" he said, "I will not give you any more trouble; I took the rug from Howard's livery-stable, in Jermyn-street;" the boots, he said, were his own, and he was in distress - his wife and children appeared to be so.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-242-person1688">
                  WILLIAM 
                  EVERETT
               <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1688" type="surname" value="EVERETT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1688" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-242-person1688" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am <rs id="t18310407-242-viclabel1296" type="occupation">coachman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-242-victim1686 t18310407-242-viclabel1296"></join> to Lord Romney, of York-street, St. James'. These boots are mine - I kept them in Howard's stable, in Jermyn-street; the prisoner had been at work for a few days there - I missed them the day after they were lost.</p>
               <p>EDWARD ROBERTS. I am groom to John Cotton, <rs id="t18310407-242-viclabel1297" type="occupation">Esq.</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-242-victim1685 t18310407-242-viclabel1297"></join>, of No.12, Carlton-chambers, Regent-street. This rug belongs to him; I did not miss it till the officer brought it me - I had seen the prisoner working two or three days at Howard's livery stables.</p>
               <p>The prisoner pleaded distress.</p>
